<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,310,400,426]" box="[189,310,400,426]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,400,426]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,400,426]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1400,447,545]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">This species is distinguished by the presence of two conspicuous wings on the dorsal sepal (vs calys without wings in all other species). It also has leaves that are rough to the touch with aciculate hairs (vs glabrous or softly hairy in all other species).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,324,583,609]" box="[189,324,583,609]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,583,609]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,583,609]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1399,630,691]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The epithet derives from the Latin ʻ 
<emphasis box="[608,673,630,655]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">asper</emphasis>
ʼ, ʻroughʼ, and ʻ 
<emphasis box="[859,934,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">folium</emphasis>
ʼ, ʻleafʼ, reflecting the rough texture the leaves of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
